1.Source Code Management (SCM)
Tools: Git, GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket
Developers push code changes to a repository.

Where Jenkins fits:
Jenkins integrates with SCM to receive webhooks on every commit/PR.
A Jenkins pipeline starts automatically when code is pushed.

2. Continuous Integration (CI)
CI ensures code changes are regularly merged and tested.

Tasks involved:
Pull latest code
Merge feature branches
Validate build
Run tests

Where Jenkins fits:
Jenkins pulls code from SCM.
Jenkins pipelines (declarative or scripted) perform CI steps.
Jenkins displays CI results (pass/fail).

3. Build & Compile Stage
Your code is compiled or packaged.
Example:
Java → mvn package
Node.js → npm build
Python → packaging wheels

Where Jenkins fits:
Runs the build using build tools (Maven, Gradle, npm, pip).
Produces a build artifact (JAR, WAR, ZIP, Docker image).


4. Automated Testing
Types of tests run here:
Unit tests
Integration tests
Regression tests
API tests


Where Jenkins fits:
Jenkins executes all automated test suites.
Outputs JUnit, NUnit, or Selenium test reports.
Marks build unstable/failed if tests fail.


5. Static Code Analysis
Tools used:
SonarQube
Checkstyle
PMD
ESLint

Where Jenkins fits:
Jenkins plugins integrate with analysis tools.
