3.What is the difference between Continuous Delivery and Continuous Deployment?
Continuous delivery
Your code is automatically built, tested, and prepared for release, but deployment to production requires a manual approval
Commit → Build → Test → Package → Deploy to Staging → (Manual Approval) → Production

Continuous deployment
Your code is automatically built, tested, packaged, and deployed all the way to production without any manual intervention.
Commit → Build → Test → Package → Deploy to Staging → Deploy to Production (automatically)

4.How do you implement automated rollback in a Jenkins pipeline?
Automated rollback in a Jenkins pipeline is implemented by adding post-deployment health checks and using a post { failure { ... } } block to trigger a script that redeploys the last known stable version or artifact.
pipeline must have a mechanism to verify the new deployment's health (e.g., calling a health endpoint, running smoke tests) after a short stabilization period.
Automate the rollback trigger: A failure in the deployment or health check stage should automatically initiate the rollback process.

When a new release fails health checks, tests, or SLO/SLA guardrails, the pipeline automatically reverts to the last known good version.
Health checks (HTTP 200 on /healthz or /readyz).
Smoke/E2E tests against the new version.
Error/latency budgets (e.g., p95 latency > threshold, error rate > X% for Y minutes).
Business KPI checks (opt‑in: sign‑ups, orders, etc.).
Alertmanager/Datadog/New Relic signals received during a bake time.

